msDesc.head: Theological miscellany: Alain de Lille, Hugo Argentinensis, Pseudo-Augustine

supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation in pencil, 1-23A, 23B-115. : older modern foliation, 89-119, struck out. mundum domini qui conditor

collation.signatures:
The manuscript exhibits four types of contemporary quire signatures, one of which is written over the previous type, revealing three separate series of numbering, which indicates that the different codicological units were assembled and rebound already in the middle ages: quire 1 is unmarked; quire 2, is marked with an abbreviated secundus inside a square frame in red ink (), the only signature of this kind. Quire 3 is marked with tertius written out (), and quire 4 with iiiius
written on the first folio of the quire (), possibly in the same hand, and possibly also on its last folio (). These quires transmit Alain of Lille's Ars praedicatoria, and the quire numbers correspond to the current structure. Quires 5-8, which transmit four collections of glosses and excerpts, seem to have once made up a separate unit: the signatures exhibit two layers, of which the first consists of Roman ordinal numerals, Ius
to IIIIus
, in red ink ( (partially erased), , , ); for the second layer, a different, contemporary hand has added a v in brown ink in front of the previous number (IIIIus
is simply crossed out and the second hand has added IXus
instead). These numbers are, however, ahead by one compared to the current structure. Quire 9, beginning the Liber soliloquiorum by Psuedo-Augustine, is simply numbered as XIus
in the same hand as the second layer of 5-8 (). A quire bearing the number X is thus missing, indicating that one full quire has been lost. The texts which remain are, however, complete.

p.note: Top left corner, in black ink over 2 lines by an early modern hand: No 195 Brocmanni; top centre, in Brocman's hand in black ink over 11 lines: a list of contents; centre right, in black ink in Brocman's hand: a note dating the manuscript to 1360; bottom centre, also in Brocman's hand: cf. Serm. Amici in 4o Bas. 1495; bottom left margin, in pencil by a modern hand: the current signum; bottom right corner: National Library book label with the current signum.

binding.p:
Medieval binding. Brown leather over bevelled wooden boards. 5 double raised bands and endbands. Hooked clasps and leather straps. , in black ink: 195
; stamped in gold: A 106.
binding.condition: Leather worn, the top half of especially. One clasp missing and half of the second clasp. The leather straps are dry and stiff.

origin.p:
Uppsala? 14th century, second half. The script used in the first two codicological units, cursiva antiquior, is mainly seen in Austria, Bohemia, Germany and Scandinavia. It does not occur before the second quarter of the 14th century and few examples exist after the beginning of the 15th century ( Derolez (2006)
). The mix of double- and single-compartment a seen in the last part of the manuscript identifies this as a late variant of the script. The colophon on gives the year for the completion of this section, and Brocman, in a note on , dates the manuscript to based on the type of paper. Brocman's identification of the contents of as explanations of difficult words in the Breviarium Upsalense would seem to indicate Uppsala as the origin.

provenance.p: Previously no. 195 in the collection of Nils Reinhold Brocman, book collector and librarian at the Royal Library and Antiquities Archive. Upon his death in , a large part of his book collection was donated to the Antiquities Archive.

acquisition.p: Transferred to the National Library from the Antiquities Archive.

msItem.title: De arte praedicatoria
msItem.explicit: a qua morte idem ipse christus nos liberare dignetur qui cum patre et filio et spiritu sancto viuit et regnat per infinita secula seculorum Amen
msItem.note: The first bifolium is missing, and the text begins in the middle of the prologue, after which follows a table of contents; at the end of the quire, the end of De luctu spirituali and the beginning of De gaudio spirituali are missing. The chapters agree for the most part with those printed by Migne; however, the last chapter, Ad somnolentos, is missing from the manuscript. The manuscript also includes two additional rubrics - Quomodo sit orandum and de septem peticionibus et pluribus que inferius continetur vltimo etc - the last of which consist of a number of sermons.

note.p: Lemmata – underlined in red – and glosses are presented in running text. Neither every psalm nor every verse of the psalms is included.

msItem.title: Exposition of the Decalogue
msItem.incipit: Si in preceptis meis ambulaueritis (Lev. 26:3) Secuntur decem precepta domini
msItem.explicit: Sodomitis offensoribus clerorum hereticis non confessis AMEN
msItem.note: The exposition ends with a concordance between the ten commandments and the ten plagues of Egypt, and after this a number of tables listing, with their definitions, the ten commandments, the seven cardinal sins, and the works of mercy.

note.p: A brief treatise on penance and episcopal and papal absolution with excerpts from Gratian's Decretals.
